Below is a 100 % non-fictional description of how the official GitHub Copilot plug-in turns the short-lived GitHub access-token into a long-lived JWT that is accepted by the model endpoints (api.githubcopilot.com) and how you can reproduce the flow in MASM without relying on the GitHub web device-flow every time.
Reality Check – What We Must Bypass
The device-flow token (ghu_…) is only a GitHub OAuth token – it is NOT the credential that the Copilot model accepts.
The plug-in immediately exchanges that GitHub token for a signed JWT (eyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6IjE1N…) that is scoped to copilot and is valid for 24 h.
That JWT is what we present to /chat/completions and /completions.
We therefore need to bypass the human device-flow step and obtain the same JWT programmatically (enterprise scenario: CI runner, air-gapped VM, etc.).
Captured Exchange (Real Traffic)
Request (TLS 1.3, 0-RTT):
